1️⃣ You Didn’t Mention Docker Layers (VERY IMPORTANT)

Docker images are built in layers.

Each Dockerfile instruction creates a layer:

FROM maven:3.9
WORKDIR /app
COPY . .
RUN mvn clean package

Each line = one layer.

Why important?

Docker caches layers

Faster rebuilds

Optimized images

Interviewers LOVE this concept.

Add this to notes:

Docker images are layered. Each instruction in Dockerfile creates a new layer, and Docker caches these layers to optimize rebuild time.

2️⃣ You Didn’t Mention Volumes vs Bind Mount Clearly

You mentioned:

docker run -v $(pwd):/app

But add this clarity:

There are two types:

Bind Mount → local folder mapped to container

Named Volume → managed by Docker

This matters when discussing persistence (like MySQL data).

3️⃣ You Didn’t Clearly Mention Data Persistence Problem

If someone runs MySQL container without volume:

Data will be lost when container is removed.

Example:

docker run mysql

Delete container → DB gone.

Correct way:

docker run -v mysql_data:/var/lib/mysql mysql

This is critical for backend devs.

4️⃣ You Slightly Mixed Two Development Styles

There are actually 2 dev workflows:

Style A – Build inside Docker

Dockerfile runs mvn clean package.

Style B – Build outside, run jar in Docker

You run:

mvn clean package

Then Dockerfile:

FROM openjdk:17
COPY target/app.jar app.jar
ENTRYPOINT ["java","-jar","app.jar"]

Both valid — but used differently.

This distinction is important in real projects.

5️⃣ You Didn’t Mention Networking Between Containers

In docker-compose:

Services can talk using service name:

services:
  app:
    depends_on:
      - mysql
  mysql:
    image: mysql

Inside app config:

spring.datasource.url=jdbc:mysql://mysql:3306/db

mysql is hostname automatically.

That’s powerful and important.

6️⃣ One Important Clarification

You wrote:

No dependency conflict if pulling same image

Correct.

But small nuance:

If teammate builds locally using Dockerfile,
dependency resolution still happens during Maven build.
So conflicts can still occur if:

pom.xml changes

Maven Central version changes

Docker doesn't freeze Maven repository state.
Only image pull freezes environment fully.

That nuance is advanced-level understanding.

7️⃣ Missing: Why Containers Are Lightweight

You didn’t mention:

Containers share host OS kernel.
VMs run full OS.

This is core conceptual difference.

Interviewers ask this often.

